title: Getting desired wire sizes for wire matching in LI11
text: The design spot size on each wire is dependent on the injector match and the beam energy, so if LEM changes or the injector is rematched you will need to update the sigma des for the wires. You can do this by measuring a multi-wire scan in X and Y and loading that data into the Optics Matching GUI (Fetch Data at the top) and then pressing Fit Emittance (on the right). These target wire sizes shouldn't be dependent on quad values you're changing, but please note if you see this change.

title: CATER 155236, Kly Mod 12-7: FLK'd, no reset.
text: Kly Mod 12-7: station thyratron not firing. Holds off HV, triggers present, but no firing. Verified HV triggers are getting to trigger grid of thyratron. Verified filament and reservoir have sufficient current and voltage to the base of the thyratron. Removed L4888 thyratron from spare mod 02-5 (HV RTM = 63240, res = 4.62 volts), S/N 100536 and installed in 12-7. Removed thyratron = Marconi (E2V) CX2410, S/N 137. 02-5 is next to 14-4. HV RTM (12-7) = 53016. Eres = 4.67 volts. MM = 15.7%. DQ = 9.5 amps. Did not get keep alive current. Station on and running stably. BV on SCP = 346 KV with 360 KV expected. PAD phase in tols with station off beam. CATER ready to close.

text: I *THINK* this was due to some shenanigans with day shift connecting the ops phone to this machine... but on the possible eve of WWIII I really don't like sketchy boxes like this inviting me to click on them to make them go away. I will end this process from the task manager to avoid clicking the boxes. Based on this warning from the Windows Event Viewer, I think these warnings are legitimate and are consequences of a real iPhone (presumably the ops phone) being connected/disconnected. I know there are lots of silly things on the Windows machine, but we should be more mindful of leaving this kind of thing lying around.

title: CATER 155239, Kly Mod 22-8: FLK'd with waveguide vac faults.
text: Kly Mod 22-8: fault log shows many, many external faults from waveguide vacuum over at least 4 days. Upon arrival, found 26 faults on the fault count. WVGC shows vac @ 3-4 E-9 with waveguide vac fault light coming on intermittently on MKSU. Energized filament a number of times. Station back on for now. Believe we have a real waveguide vacuum issue here or the gauge itself is flaky. CATER ready to close.

title: Concerning warnings on the shared Windows machine?
text: I *THINK* this was due to some shenanigans with day shift connecting the ops phone to this machine to transfer some pictures of the ceiling... but on the possible eve of WWIII I really don't like sketchy boxes like this inviting me to click on them to make them go away. I closed these windows from the taskbar (couldn't do it from Task Manager without getting a warning). Based on this warning from the Windows Event Viewer, I think these warnings are legitimate and are consequences of a real iPhone (presumably the ops phone) being connected/disconnected. I know there are lots of silly things on the Windows machine, but we should be more mindful of leaving this kind of thing lying around.

Shopwork - Repair MCOR Crate
text: Background: A MCOR crate (PCD00178) which was removed from LI15 was setup and tested at the test-stand. It was running for two days full operation. Day 3 in the morning, the unit begin to see some fault at channel 12, 14, and 15, Reset/clear faults and the station working again. Around the afternoon we start to notice burning smell and see the Bulk supply input current is 5Amp higher than the nominal. Turn off the Bulk supply and reset the MCOR crate power and operate again. Unfortunate, there is no output on channel 12, 14, and 15. 2/18/22 Troubleshooting: Start to isolate MCOR boards in Ch12, 14, and 15 and no output shows with a known working board. Further looking into the crate and find the output connector J7 and J8 were burnt/melted and unable to recover. Remove the crate and find that the mating connector also defective as part this failure. Repair: Find two more crates (PCD00165 and PCD00188) in the shop that has one output connector damages. MCOR crate PCD00178 was used for part to repair the two crates PCD00165 and PCD00188. Replace the output mating ribbon connector, and MCOR crate PCD00188 J8 output connector was repaired and setup to run over weekend. MCOR crate PCD00165 is expected to be complete next week.

title: 22-3: Constant BVJ on CUD Display CATER 155243
text: Klystron CUD showing constant BVJ, yet signal from klystron show very low jitter. After doing some research, saw that the +5V_Ref signal on PIOP was going out of tolerance. This signal is the DC reference for the internal ADC on the MKSU for digitizing analog signals from the modulator. History plot showed this signal to be very noisy when compared to 2 other stations. After MKSU swap (PCD03427 out, PDC03612 in, DEPOT updated), signal noise is gone. BVJ gone from the CUD display. Readjusted PIOP ratios for BV and BC. The FTP showed a two-step BV jitter signal before swap, now show a very nice low jitter signal. Adding photo to elog showing before and after swap of the reference voltage. Note: The Vres kept getting adjusted for this BVJ on the display, which did not need to happen (caused HVOC's when set too high). Did adjust Vres to 4.55V from 4.50V to keep jitter very low. ct/rm

title: How to wake up the BC14 feedback when it gets stuck
text: BC14 energy feedback is running using 14-4 and 14-5 phases to regulate energy. This feedback requires 14-4 to be at a negative phase, and 14-5 to be at a positive phase. Sometimes the phase shifters for either of these stations will flip into the wrong sign and the feedback will stop trying, at which point you'll have to manually set one of the PDES values to within its range and trim it. If you see the BC14 energy BPM drift away from 0 (and not because we are just off energy) it's worth checking that the phases are in their ranges.

title: Experimenting with 10-2 Fast feedback to see if peak power faults go away
text: We've disabled the fast feedback and re-enabled the slow feedback for the gun to see if any inputs to the fast feedback on the AMC card are temperature sensitive. We'll want this to stay off to see if it makes the peak power faults go away. If we get a few peak power faults we can re-enable this as it wouldn't be the culprit, although it doesn't seem to matter really. It's worth noting that now disabling the fast feedbacks also disables the slow feedbacks. The slow feedbacks are not re-enabled automatically when the fast feedbacks are turned back on.
